\[ D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE} \]

The zero-point energy is given by:

\[ \text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e \]

where \( \omega_e = 1405.65  \text{cm}^{-1} \) and \( \omega_e x_e = 23.20  \text{cm}^{-1} \).

Substituting the values:

\[ \frac{1}{2} \omega_e = \frac{1}{2} \times 1405.65 = 702.825  \text{cm}^{-1} \]

\[ \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e = \frac{1}{4} \times 23.20 = 5.80  \text{cm}^{-1} \]

\[ \text{ZPE} = 702.825 - 5.80 = 697.025  \text{cm}^{-1} \]

Convert ZPE from cm\(^{-1}\) to eV using the conversion factor \( 1  \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.23984 \times 10^{-4}  \text{eV} \):

\[ \text{ZPE}_{\text{eV}} = 697.025 \times 1.23984 \times 10^{-4} = 0.086420  \text{eV} \]

Now calculate \( D_e \):

\[ D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE}_{\text{eV}} = 2.4287 + 0.086420 = 2.515120  \text{eV} \]

