The solution calculates a lower bound for \( P\left(\left| \frac{Y}{n} - 0.25 \right| < 0.05\right) \) when \( n = 500 \) and \( Y \sim b(n, 0.25) \) using Chebyshev's inequality. The variance of the sample proportion \( \hat{p} = \frac{Y}{n} \) is \( \sigma^2 = \frac{p(1-p)}{n} = \frac{0.25 \times 0.75}{500} = 0.000375 \). With \( d = 0.05 \), so \( d^2 = 0.0025 \), Chebyshev's inequality gives:

\[
P\left(\left| \hat{p} - p \right| < d\right) \geq 1 - \frac{\sigma^2}{d^2} = 1 - \frac{0.000375}{0.0025} = 1 - 0.15 = 0.85
\]

