Solution: The problem requires approximating \(P(1/2 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) where \(\bar{X}\) is the sample mean of a random sample of size 12 from a uniform distribution on the interval \((0,1)\).

The uniform distribution on \((0,1)\) has mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2 = 1/12\). For a sample size of \(n = 12\), the sample mean \(\bar{X}\) has mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2_{\bar{X}} = \sigma^2 / n = (1/12)/12 = 1/144\). The standard deviation of \(\bar{X}\) is \(\sigma_{\bar{X}} = \sqrt{1/144} = 1/12\).

By the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed for large \(n\). Although \(n = 12\) is relatively small, the uniform distribution is symmetric and the normal approximation is reasonable here.

The probability \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) is standardized using the Z-score formula:
- Lower bound: \(Z = (0.5 - 0.5) / (1/12) = 0\)
- Upper bound: \(Z = (2/3 - 0.5) / (1/12) = (1/6) / (1/12) = 2\)

Thus, the probability is \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\) for a standard normal variable \(Z\). Using standard normal tables or approximations:
- \(P(Z \leq 2) \approx 0.9772\)
- \(P(Z \leq 0) = 0.5\)
