Problem: A doctor is concerned about the relationship between blood pressure and irregular heartbeats. Among her patients, she classifies blood pressures as high, normal, or low and heartbeats as regular or irregular and finds that 16\% have high blood pressure; (b) 19\% have low blood pressure; (c) $17 \%$ have an irregular heartbeat; (d) of those with an irregular heartbeat, $35 \%$ have high blood pressure; and (e) of those with normal blood pressure, $11 \%$ have an irregular heartbeat. What percentage of her patients have a regular heartbeat and low blood pressure? The unit of the answer should be % .
Solution: To find the percentage of patients with a regular heartbeat and low blood pressure, the given information is used step by step.

- 16% of patients have high blood pressure (P(H) = 16%).
- 19% have low blood pressure (P(L) = 19%).
- 17% have an irregular heartbeat (P(I) = 17%).
- Of those with irregular heartbeat, 35% have high blood pressure (P(H|I) = 35%).
- Of those with normal blood pressure, 11% have irregular heartbeat (P(I|N) = 11%).

First, the percentage with normal blood pressure is calculated as:  
P(N) = 100% - P(H) - P(L) = 100% - 16% - 19% = 65%.

Next, the joint percentage with irregular heartbeat and high blood pressure is:  
P(H ∩ I) = P(H|I) × P(I) = 35% × 17% = 5.95%.

The joint percentage with irregular heartbeat and normal blood pressure is:  
P(I ∩ N) = P(I|N) × P(N) = 11% × 65% = 7.15%.

The joint percentage with irregular heartbeat and low blood pressure is found using the total irregular heartbeat percentage:  
P(I ∩ L) = P(I) - P(H ∩ I) - P(I ∩ N) = 17% - 5.95% - 7.15% = 3.9%.

The percentage with low blood pressure and regular heartbeat is then:  
P(R ∩ L) = P(L) - P(I ∩ L) = 19% - 3.9% = 15.1%.

The result is rounded to one decimal place for consistency with the input percentages and calculations.

Summary: The final answer is 15.1
