Solution: The probability of drawing a white chip, \(P(W)\), is calculated using the law of total probability. The probabilities of selecting each bowl and the conditional probabilities of drawing a white chip given each bowl are as follows:

- \(P(B_1) = \frac{1}{2}\), \(P(W \mid B_1) = 1\) (since bowl \(B_1\) has 2 white chips out of 2).
- \(P(B_2) = \frac{1}{4}\), \(P(W \mid B_2) = 0\) (since bowl \(B_2\) has 0 white chips out of 2).
- \(P(B_3) = \frac{1}{8}\), \(P(W \mid B_3) = \frac{2}{4} = 0.5\) (since bowl \(B_3\) has 2 white chips out of 4).
- \(P(B_4) = \frac{1}{8}\), \(P(W \mid B_4) = \frac{3}{4} = 0.75\) (since bowl \(B_4\) has 3 white chips out of 4).

The total probability is:
\[
P(W) = \left(\frac{1}{2} \times 1\right) + \left(\frac{1}{4} \times 0\right) + \left(\frac{1}{8} \times 0.5\right) + \left(\frac{1}{8} \times 0.75\right)
\]

